TABLE S18: METHODOLOGICAL FOOTNOTES AND STATISTICAL FRAMEWORK
================================================================================

1. MULTIPLE COMPARISON CORRECTION
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Between-group comparisons (Kruskal-Wallis) were followed by Mann-Whitney U 
   post-hoc tests. Bonferroni correction was applied for all post-hoc 
   comparisons. Adjusted alpha = 0.017 per comparison (family-wise alpha = 0.05). 
   Within-group repeated measures: Bonferroni correction (5 outcomes per group); 
   Adjusted alpha = 0.01 per test.

2. EFFECT SIZE INTERPRETATION
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Effect sizes for ordinal non-parametric outcomes were calculated using 
   Cliff's Delta (|d|). Magnitude thresholds followed established conventions 
   for ordinal effect size interpretation (Vargha & Delaney, 2000): 
   negligible (|d| < 0.147), small (0.147 ≤ |d| < 0.33), medium 
   (0.33 ≤ |d| < 0.474), and large (|d| ≥ 0.474). Effect size estimates 
   should be interpreted cautiously in small pilot studies because magnitude 
   estimates may be inflated relative to true population effects 
   (Button et al., 2013; Leon et al., 2011).

3. NON-PARAMETRIC JUSTIFICATION
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Given the exploratory pilot design, ordinal clinical outcomes, and small 
   sample size, non-parametric methods were prioritized. Shapiro-Wilk test 
   rejected normality for most ordinal variables (p < 0.05). Parametric 
   methods were applied only when distributional assumptions were satisfied; 
   otherwise, non-parametric approaches were retained.

4. BASELINE BALANCE
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   All baseline parameters were balanced across groups (all p > 0.05), 
   confirming successful randomization and sex stratification.

5. EXPLORATORY OUTCOME
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Local SCORAD† was prespecified in the amended Statistical Analysis Plan 
   (SAP) v2.0 (finalized before database lock). Marked with † in all 
   manuscript figures/tables.

6. DATA SOURCE & COMPLETENESS
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Source: DEPRO_Study_Data.xlsx | Total: n = 30 (Group A: n=10, Group B: n=10, 
   Group C: n=10). Given minimal missing data, complete-case analysis was applied.

7. SIGNIFICANCE CRITERION
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Two-tailed tests throughout. Threshold: p < 0.05 (unadjusted) or 
   p < 0.017 (Bonferroni-adjusted post-hoc comparisons).

8. EXPLORATORY POST-HOC POWER ESTIMATION
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Performed using G*Power (v3.1.9.7). See Supplementary Table S11.

9. FUTURE DEFINITIVE TRIAL PLANNING
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Effect size estimates should be interpreted with extreme caution. Ordinal scales with limited category ranges and small pilot samples (n = 10 per group) may yield inflated non-parametric effect sizes approaching the theoretical ceiling (|d| = 1.00). As emphasized by Leon et al. (2011), pilot studies are not designed to provide precise effect size estimates for planning definitive trials. The large Cliff's Delta values observed in this study (≥ 0.92) should be viewed as exploratory indicators of signal direction and magnitude rather than reliable estimates of true clinical effect. Future confirmatory studies should employ larger samples (n ≥ 71 per group, see Section B above) and validated continuous outcome measures to obtain stable effect size estimates.

   Sample size requirements for future confirmatory studies were estimated 
   using a clinically meaningful comparable exploratory performance framework 
   rather than observed pilot effect sizes. A comparable exploratory 
   performance margin of 0.5 points on the 5-point Clinical Dryness Score 
   was prespecified because it represents less than one categorical severity 
   grade and was considered the largest difference unlikely to be clinically 
   meaningful in routine dermocosmetic use. Using Noether's formula (1987) for 
   a two-sided Mann-Whitney U test (alpha = 0.05, power = 0.90) and incorporating 
   a 20% anticipated attrition rate, a future confirmatory comparative trial 
   would require approximately n ≈ 71 participants per group (N = 213 total) 
   to confirm comparable efficacy between crude propolis and EEP 
   (Supplementary Table S11).

10. CEILING EFFECT TRANSPARENCY
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    The HCP-KAP-TCS v1.0 instrument exhibited severe ceiling effects, with 
    15 of 36 items (41.7%) showing zero variance (Knowledge: K1–K6; Attitude: 
    A4, A6, A8, A10; Practice: P2, P4, P6, P8, P10). Both full-scale and 
    discriminating-item subset analyses are reported throughout this 
    supplementary document to ensure transparency. Discriminating-item scores 
    exclude zero-variance items and better reflect true expertise gradients, 
    whereas full-scale scores are provided for comparison with prior literature 
    using conventional KAP scoring approaches.
11.INSTRUMENT VALIDATION LIMITATION
The KAP instruments (Public and HCP versions) were developed through literature review and expert panel consultation but were not subjected to formal psychometric validation (content validity index, confirmatory factor analysis, test-retest reliability). Therefore, all domain scores, level classifications, and inter-domain correlations should be regarded as exploratory indicators rather than validated psychometric constructs. This limitation constrains the strength of inferences regarding construct validity and score stability. Future studies should establish content validity index (CVI ≥ 0.80) and test-retest reliability (ICC ≥ 0.70) before confirmatory use.

